#: src/updater/overview.md:225
msgid "Install + rollback flow"
msgstr "Flux d'installation et de rollback"

#: src/updater/overview.md:227
msgid ""
"```text\n"
"manifest fetch  â  semver compare  â  download to <exe>.staged\n"
"                                          â\n"
"                                      sha256 verify  â  ed25519 verify\n"
"                                          â\n"
"                                      arm sentinel (state: \"armed\")\n"
"                                          â\n"
"                                      install:  rename <exe> â <exe>.prev\n"
"                                                rename <exe>.staged â <exe>\n"
"                                                chmod +x   (Unix only)\n"
"                                          â\n"
"                                      detached relaunch  â  process.exit(0)\n"
"\n"
"next boot  â  initUpdater() reads sentinel\n"
"                  âââ healthCheckMs alive  â clearSentinel  (success)\n"
"                  âââ graceful exit         â clearSentinel  (success)\n"
"                  âââ restartCount âĨ N      â performRollback + exit\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/updater/overview.md:246
msgid ""
"`installUpdate` is atomic where the OS lets us be: POSIX `rename(2)` on the "
"same filesystem, NTFS rename-while-open (the PE loader opens with "
"`FILE_SHARE_DELETE` so Windows tolerates this since Vista), and Linux's "
"mmap'd-inode-stays-alive semantics. If the staging directory ends up on a "
"different filesystem (a separate mount for `/tmp`, for instance) the rename "
"falls back to copy + remove, which has a small non-atomic window."
msgstr ""
"`installUpdate` est atomique lÃ  oÃđ l'OS nous le permet : `rename(2)` POSIX "
"sur le mÃŠme systÃĻme de fichiers, renommage NTFS pendant l'ouverture (le "
"chargeur PE ouvre avec `FILE_SHARE_DELETE`, donc Windows tolÃĻre cela depuis "
"Vista), et la sÃĐmantique Linux oÃđ l'inode mappÃĐ en mÃĐmoire reste actif. Si "
"le rÃĐpertoire de staging se retrouve sur un systÃĻme de fichiers diffÃĐrent "
"(un montage sÃĐparÃĐ pour `/tmp`, par exemple), le renommage se replie sur "
"copie + suppression, ce qui comporte une petite fenÃŠtre non atomique."

